Step 1: Prerequisites¶

Gather and label image.¶

  • Label Studio is used to prepare dataset for this notebook.
  • Annotated images were exported as Pascal VOC dataset.
  • This dataset is then compressed as zip file.

# create main directory
os.makedirs(root_dir, exist_ok=True)

subdirs = ['workspace/proj_facemask',
           'workspace/proj_facemask/annotations', 'workspace/proj_facemask/exported-models',
           'workspace/proj_facemask/images', 'workspace/proj_facemask/images/test', 'workspace/proj_facemask/images/train',
           'workspace/proj_facemask/models', 'workspace/proj_facemask/pre-trained-models']

concat_root_path = partial(os.path.join, root_dir)
make_directory = partial(os.makedirs, exist_ok=True)

# create folders for every paths in subdirs
for path_items in map(concat_root_path, subdirs):
    make_directory(path_items)

# Extract dataset to current session
for i in ['/content/annotations.zip', '/content/images.zip']:
  zip_ref = zipfile.ZipFile(i, 'r') # Opens the zip file in read mode
  zip_ref.extractall('/content') # Extracts the files into the /content folder
  zip_ref.close()
In [10]:
test_size = 0.2

# get all images and annotations paths
images_path_sorted = sorted(next(os.walk('/content/images'), (None, None, []))[2])
annotations_path_sorted = sorted(next(os.walk('/content/annotations'), (None, None, []))[2])

# split train and test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(images_path_sorted, annotations_path_sorted, test_size = test_size, random_state=0)
print('Total train images:', len(X_train))
print('Total test images:', len(X_test))

In [11]:
# copy to destination folders
def copy_images(image_path, label_path, destination_folder):
  """
  Copy images and annotations into "data/{destination_folder}"
  """
  print(f"[INFO] Copying files from /content/.. to {destination_folder}")
  for image_path, label_path in zip(image_path, label_path):
    # Copy images and label path into the destination folder
    shutil.copy2(os.path.join('/content/images', image_path), destination_folder)
    shutil.copy2(os.path.join('/content/annotations', label_path), destination_folder)
  print("[INFO] Files copied successfully")
In [104]:
copy_images(X_train, y_train, path_dir['TRAIN'])
copy_images(X_test, y_test, path_dir['TEST'])

4. Create and add label_map.pbtxt¶

Destination folder: proj_facemask/annotations.

In [144]:
CLASS_NAMES = ['facemask']
LABEL_MAP_NAME = 'label_map.pbtxt'

with open(os.path.join(path_dir['ANNOTATIONS'], LABEL_MAP_NAME), 'w') as f:
  for idx, label in enumerate(CLASS_NAMES, start=1):
    f.write("item { \n")
    f.write(f"\tname: \'{label}\'\n")
    f.write(f"\tid: {idx}\n")
    f.write("}\n")

5. Download and add the generate_tfrecord.py script¶

In [238]:
tf_generator = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ansonnn07/object-detection/main/utils/generate_tfrecord.py"
r = requests.get(tf_generator, allow_redirects=True)

with open(os.path.join(root_dir, 'workspace', current_project, 'generate_tfrecord.py'), 'wb') as f:
  f.write(r.content)

6. Download and extract pre-trained model¶

  • Choose a model to download from TensorFlow Model Zoo. (Right click on model name and copy link address)
  • Extract and save model using get_file() function in proj_facemask/pre-trained-models.
In [107]:
from tensorflow.python.keras.utils.data_utils import get_file

# link address for model to download
modelURL = "http://download.tensorflow.org/models/object_detection/tf2/20200711/ssd_mobilenet_v2_320x320_coco17_tpu-8.tar.gz"
filename = os.path.basename(modelURL)
In [108]:
# download and extract model
# need to specify cache_subdir='' otherwise it will save under another subfolder called '/datasets/' (not sure why)
get_file(fname=filename, origin=modelURL, cache_dir=path_dir['PRE_TRAINED_MODELS'], cache_subdir='', extract=True)
Out[108]:
'/content/gdrive/MyDrive/mida_deep_learning/custom_detector/workspace/proj_facemask/pre-trained-models/ssd_mobilenet_v2_320x320_coco17_tpu-8.tar.gz'

7. Create a new folder for pre-train model¶

Assuming the downloaded model was ssd_resnet_v1_fpn:

  • Go to proj_facemask/models and make a new folder named my_ssd_resnet_v1_fpn (name the folder according to the pre-trained-model you have downloaded)
  • Copy the pipeline.config file from proj_facemask/pre-trained-models/ssd_resnet50_v1_fpn_640x640_coco17_tpu-8 (or from the respective folder of the pre-trained-model you have downloaded and extracted) and paste it into the newly created my_ssd_resnet_v1_fpn folder (or the folder new you created in proj_facemask/models according to your pre-trained-model).
In [109]:
MODELNAME = filename[:filename.index('.')]
MY_MODEL_NAME = 'my_' + MODELNAME
In [110]:
# Create a new folder named `my_{name of model you downloaded}`
os.makedirs(os.path.join(path_dir['MY_MODELS'], MY_MODEL_NAME), exist_ok=True)

Step 6: Build and Install setup.py¶

# Credit: https://github.com/ansonnn07/object-detection

print("[INFO] Downloading protobuf dependencies ...")
version = '3.19.1'
url=f"https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/releases/download/v{version}/protoc-{version}-win64.zip"
wget.download(url)
# move the protoc zip file into the desired path, PROTOC_PATH
if not os.path.exists(path_dir['PROTOC_PATH']):
    shutil.move(f"protoc-{version}-win64.zip", path_dir['PROTOC_PATH'])
# unzip the zip file
if os.name == 'nt':
    # Windows must use `tar` for unzipping zipfile
    !cd {path_dir['PROTOC_PATH']} && tar -xf protoc-{version}-win64.zip
else:
    # Linux must use `unzip`
    !cd {path_dir['PROTOC_PATH']} && unzip protoc-{version}-win64.zip
# add the path of $PROTOC_PATH/bin into the PATH in environment variable
# to be able to run `protoc` as a command in terminal
os.environ['PATH'] += os.pathsep + os.path.abspath(os.path.join(path_dir['PROTOC_PATH'], 'bin'))   
# run the `protoc` command and install all the dependencies for TFOD API
!cd /content/gdrive/MyDrive/mida_deep_learning/custom_detector/models/research && protoc object_detection/protos/*.proto --python_out=. && cp object_detection/packages/tf2/setup.py . && python -m pip install --use-feature=2020-resolver .
!cd /content/gdrive/MyDrive/mida_deep_learning/custom_detector/models/research/slim && pip install -e .

import tensorflow as tf 
raw_dataset = tf.data.TFRecordDataset(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'annotations', 'train.record'))

for raw_record in raw_dataset.take(1):
    example = tf.train.Example()
    example.ParseFromString(raw_record.numpy())
    print(example)

import tensorflow as tf 
raw_dataset = tf.data.TFRecordDataset(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'annotations', 'test.record'))

for raw_record in raw_dataset.take(1):
    example = tf.train.Example()
    example.ParseFromString(raw_record.numpy())
    print(example)

In [299]:
# Change number of classes
config_util._update_num_classes(config['model'], num_classes)

# Change batch size
config_util._update_batch_size(config, batch_size)

# Change checkpoint type
config['train_config'].fine_tune_checkpoint = fine_tune_checkpoint

# Change fine tune checkpoint type
config['train_config'].fine_tune_checkpoint_type = fine_tune_checkpoint_type

# Change label map path
config_util._update_label_map_path(config, label_map_path)

# Change .record files for both train and test
config_util._update_tf_record_input_path(config['train_input_config'], train_tfrecord)
config_util._update_tf_record_input_path(config['eval_input_configs'][0], test_tfrecord)

# Remove the existing config file and save the custom changes as new config file
os.remove(files_path['MY_MODEL_PIPELINE_CONFIG'])
pipeline_config = config_util.create_pipeline_proto_from_configs(config)
config_util.save_pipeline_config(pipeline_config, os.path.join(path_dir['MY_MODELS'], MY_MODEL_NAME))

Step 10: Train model¶

but first, double check installation¶

Checking !pip list show that opencv-python-headless doesn't match the other opencv-* packages. So uninstall opencv-python-headless==4.5.5.64 and install opencv-python-headless==4.1.2.30

else:
    print("Please install GPU version of TF")

tf.config.experimental.set_visible_devices([], 'GPU')

WARNING:tensorflow:From /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/tensorflow/python/autograph/impl/api.py:459: py_func (from tensorflow.python.ops.script_ops) is deprecated and will be removed in a future version.
Instructions for updating:
tf.py_func is deprecated in TF V2. Instead, there are two
    options available in V2.
    - tf.py_function takes a python function which manipulates tf eager
    tensors instead of numpy arrays. It's easy to convert a tf eager tensor to
    an ndarray (just call tensor.numpy()) but having access to eager tensors
    means `tf.py_function`s can use accelerators such as GPUs as well as
    being differentiable using a gradient tape.
    - tf.numpy_function maintains the semantics of the deprecated tf.py_func
    (it is not differentiable, and manipulates numpy arrays). It drops the
    stateful argument making all functions stateful.

    options available in V2.

    an ndarray (just call tensor.numpy()) but having access to eager tensors

    being differentiable using a gradient tape.

    (it is not differentiable, and manipulates numpy arrays). It drops the
    stateful argument making all functions stateful.

#Import the required libraries for Object detection infernece
import time
import tensorflow as tf
from object_detection.utils import label_map_util
from object_detection.utils import visualization_utils as viz_utils
import os
import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

# Loading the exported model from the saved_model directory
PATH_TO_SAVED_MODEL = os.path.join(OUTPUT_PATH, "saved_model")

print('Loading model...', end='')
start_time = time.perf_counter()
# LOAD SAVED MODEL AND BUILD DETECTION FUNCTION
detect_fn = tf.saved_model.load(PATH_TO_SAVED_MODEL)
end_time = time.perf_counter()
print(f'Done! Took {end_time - start_time} seconds')

Step 14: Deploy model¶

In [270]:
from imutils.paths import list_images
import numpy as np

def load_image_into_numpy_array(path):
    """Load an image from file into a numpy array.
    Puts image into numpy array of shape (height, width, channels), where channels=3 for RGB to feed into tensorflow graph.
    Args:
      path: the file path to the image
    Returns:
      uint8 numpy array with shape (img_height, img_width, 3)
    """
    img = cv2.imread(path)
    # convert from OpenCV's BGR to RGB format
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    return np.array(img)

def detect(image_np):
    start_t = time.perf_counter()
    # Running the infernce on the image specified in the  image path
    # The input needs to be a tensor, convert it using `tf.convert_to_tensor`.
    input_tensor = tf.convert_to_tensor(image_np)
    # The model expects a batch of images, so add an axis with `tf.expand_dims`.
    input_tensor = input_tensor[tf.newaxis, ...]
    # input_tensor = tf.expand_dims(input_tensor, 0)

    # running detection using the loaded model
    detections = detect_fn(input_tensor)

    # All outputs are batches tensors.
    # Convert to numpy arrays, and take index [0] to remove the batch dimension.
    # We're only interested in the first num_detections.
    num_detections = int(detections.pop('num_detections'))
    detections = {key: value[0, :num_detections].numpy()
                   for key, value in detections.items()}
    detections['num_detections'] = num_detections

    # detection_classes should be ints.
    detections['detection_classes'] = detections['detection_classes'].astype(np.int64)
    #print(detections['detection_classes'])
    end_t = time.perf_counter()
    print(f'[INFO] Done inference. [{end_t - start_t:.2f} secs]')
    
    return detections

def draw_results(detections, image_np, min_score_thresh=0.6):
    label_id_offset = 1
    image_np_with_detections = image_np.copy()
    viz_utils.visualize_boxes_and_labels_on_image_array(
                image_np_with_detections,
                detections['detection_boxes'],
                # detections['detection_classes'] + label_id_offset,
                detections['detection_classes'],
                detections['detection_scores'],
                category_index,
                use_normalized_coordinates=True,
                max_boxes_to_draw=20,
                min_score_thresh=min_score_thresh,
                agnostic_mode=False
    )
    return image_np_with_detections

In [282]:
img_paths = list(list_images(path_dir['TEST']))

# setting min confidence threshold
# lower this to obtain more detections
MIN_CONF_THRESH=0.8

for p in np.random.choice(img_paths, 4, replace=False):
    image_np = load_image_into_numpy_array(p)
    print(f"[INFO] Detecting from the image {p} ...")
    detections = detect(image_np)
    image_np_with_detections = draw_results(detections, image_np, MIN_CONF_THRESH)

    fig = plt.figure()
    fig.set_size_inches(10, 10)
    plt.imshow(image_np_with_detections)
    plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Conclusion & recommendation¶

  • Model performance is very poor as we can observe same position of bounding boxes in all of the above predictions - may benefit from more training & data.
  • Experiment with other models from Model Zoo! 😌
